      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i'm looking at our quarterly reports for the electronics warehouse and our shrinkage numbers are way higher than usual. we're seeing a lot of missing small components and high-value peripheral items. i need to figure out how this level of shrinkage is actually hitting our inventory turnover ratio. can you walk me through the math and how to factor this in?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Shrinkage, a lost piece of the puzzle, is a real headache. You'll need to look at the inventory turnover ratio, but first, you need to make sure you're accounting for the *lost* inventory. If you don't, your turnover ratio will look deceptively good, which is worse than a slow-moving pile of old gear.\n\nHere's the basic math, but don't let the numbers scare you. The turnover ratio is generally calculated as:\n\n**Inventory Turnover Ratio = Cost of Goods Sold (COGS) / Average Inventory Value**\n\nThe problem is, your \"Average Inventory Value\" is inflated because it includes items that aren't actually there—the missing components. You need to adjust your inventory value downward to reflect the true, usable stock.\n\nSo, the adjustment looks like this:\n\n1.  **Calculate Actual Inventory:** Take your reported inventory value and subtract the estimated or actual shrinkage amount.\n    *   *Actual Inventory = Reported Inventory - Shrinkage Value*\n2.  **Calculate Adjusted COGS:** Similarly, if the missing items were part of what you *thought* you sold, you need to adjust your COGS to reflect what actually",
